<subsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-an-annulus" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Area of an Annulus</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_39e1h6ms">
            <p xml:id="auto_6slotua6">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_inldm56b">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_en75zurt">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_x0he7dwq">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_p0ia41c6">
                        2.6 Area of a Part of a Circle
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tyaxvq15">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_3ra36yor">
                        Determine the area of an annulus in different situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_7l47r8h3" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_zfprcndk">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_rrxsxrxy" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_0o2o58ll">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_szzrw8af" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_1hwykqe4"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ipgdfq5q">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ktxouw64">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define an annulus and explain that its area is the difference between the areas of the outer and inner circles.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_y3ugsnf3">
                        <p xml:id="auto_8oxu67mo">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the area of an annulus using <m>A = \pi(R^2 - r^2)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_m1foary3">
                        <p xml:id="auto_nlfrhfs5">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-life problems involving annular regions, such as running tracks, pipes and wheels.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_ei5n4tkg">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-a-part-of-a-circle/area-of-an-annulus.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_7gibkgz1">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-a-part-of-a-circle/step-by-step-guide_area-of-an-annulus.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_h66nxtvo">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_aw376z0j">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Work in groups (Activity 1), then individual work (Activity 2)
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gy4jqrpo">
            <alert>Teacher Questions During Discovery:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_froxozdq">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_5cg2qa0e">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ze1mioth"><q>What shape is created when you place a smaller circle inside a larger circle?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zjj6vlry">
                    <p xml:id="auto_kvflpy2m"><q>How did you calculate the area of the ring?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xgldybxy">
                    <p xml:id="auto_py4ga0d6"><q>What pattern did you notice when calculating the area?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_27n6zdkr">
                    <p xml:id="auto_qqfbotea"><q>Did different circular objects give you the same formula?</q></p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_5c8w7kfw">
            <alert>Teacher Role:</alert> Circulate among groups, ensuring learners measure the radii accurately. For struggling groups, prompt: <q>Let us start by finding the area of the larger circle first. Then find the area of the smaller circle. What do we do next?</q> For early finishers: <q>Can you write a general formula for finding the area of any annulus?</q> Identify 2–3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_h7yc0jwx">
            <alert>Expected Responses:</alert> The area of an annulus equals the area of the outer circle minus the area of the inner circle.
        </p>
    </axiom>



   
    <activity xml:id="auto_rf45rkoc">
        <p xml:id="auto_ebq1ldj0">
            <m>\textbf{Work in groups  }</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_1g6vrq3w">
            <alert>What you require:</alert> Circular objects (e.g., two different-sized cups, lids, or rings), ruler or measuring tape and 
            pen and paper (or a calculator).

        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ye9s55zl">
            <ol xml:id="auto_myd9vads">
                <li xml:id="auto_2tzbhujc">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ouvj9ciz">
                        Look around your surroundings and find two circular objects that can fit inside each other 
                        (e.g., two different-sized bowls, two bottle caps, or two CDs).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ij3283tf">
                    <p xml:id="auto_lxizxcv3">
                        Place the smaller object inside 
                        the larger one to visualize the annulus (ring shape).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_1zur9hu2">
                    <p xml:id="auto_k9r3szmn">
                        Record the values.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_a6c9nh5g">
                        <ul xml:id="auto_jqq8q6r8">
                            <li xml:id="auto_zm3bq5q6">
                                <p xml:id="auto_8rtjzi3w">
                                    Measure the radius of the larger circle (<m>R</m>) from its center to the edge.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_ircejkrx">
                                <p xml:id="auto_01lr0rxj">
                                    Measure the radius of the smaller circle (<m>r</m>) in the same way.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_c7lh2e8o">
                    <p xml:id="auto_h875i9gi">
                        Square both radii. and record your result.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_x955hxf6">
                        Subtract the squared radius of the smaller circle from the squared radius of the larger circle.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ekikyfy6">
                        Multiply the result by <m>\frac{22}{7}</m> or <m>3.142</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mlj2qeej">
                    <p xml:id="auto_0t6v1xwz">
                        Discuss with your group how to calculate the area of an annulus.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_l7s1mbfu">
                    <p xml:id="auto_eyaoty6c">
                        Try this activity with different circular objects and compare your results.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p xml:id="auto_bksq29j3">
        <m>\textbf{Extended Activity}</m>
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="auto_2a6p6xj4">
        <p xml:id="auto_ype91dym">
            <m>\textbf{Individual work}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qubiyc4x">
            <term>Situation:</term>  Imagine a running track built around a circular field. The track has an inner boundary (smaller circle) and an outer 
            boundary (larger circle). The track itself forms an annulus.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_9mxromlj">
            <ul xml:id="auto_fykqhm5q">
                <li xml:id="auto_0xds1ekj">
                    <p xml:id="auto_th0b6wmt">
                        A school is planning to paint the running track.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_f5xdhkhu">
                    <p xml:id="auto_82psnshc">
                        The inner radius of the track is <m>30</m> meters, and the outer radius is <m>35</m> meters.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_w5cd1rk7">
                    <p xml:id="auto_tlmj3ioi">
                        The cost of painting is Ksh <m>5</m> per square meter
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_l1rskxcx">
                    <p xml:id="auto_7ajbq9m8">
                        Calculate:
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_a4kygn03">
                        <ol xml:id="auto_eltiypkn">
                            <li xml:id="auto_zdgpsx1o">
                                <p xml:id="auto_uv348pas">
                                    The area of the track
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_li0p8a8v">
                                <p xml:id="auto_fzr2bwhu">
                                    The total cost of painting the track.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_gq8pytmg">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_meak870d">
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_43mbbh1y">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_0ycgmicy">
                    <p xml:id="auto_zndjui6i"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I can use the diameter directly in the formula.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> The formula uses radius, not diameter. If given diameter, divide by 2 first.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pqycv9by">
                    <p xml:id="auto_jp6gtk7f"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I subtract the radii first, then square.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> You must square each radius first, then subtract: <m>\pi(R^2 - r^2)</m>, not <m>\pi(R - r)^2</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bxweneyw">
                    <p xml:id="auto_zp89d9ek"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>The two circles must touch.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> The circles are concentric (share the same centre) but the inner circle is smaller; they do not touch.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_309j9i7l">
                    <p xml:id="auto_efw5gxpj"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I can use different centres for the two circles.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> Both circles must share the same centre to form an annulus.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>


    <p xml:id="auto_kfaptp6k">
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_5b0dugpr">
        An <m>\textbf{annulus}</m> is the region between two concentric circles that share the same center but have different
        radii as shown below. 
    </p>
     <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="Annulus">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw the outer circle in blue
            \fill[very thick,cyan] (0,0) circle (2);
            % Draw the inner circle in white
            \fill[very thick ,white] (0,0) circle (1);
            
            % Draw radius lines
            \draw[very thick,thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (0:1) ;
            \draw[very thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (120:2) node[midway, right] {$R$};
            
            % Draw center mark
            \draw[very thick] (-0.15,0) -- (0.15,0);
            \draw[very thick] (0,-0.15) -- (0,0.15);
            
           
            
            \node [below]at (0.5,0) {$r$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
        
        
    </image>

    <p xml:id="auto_c17z5qgh"> The area of an annulus (a ring-shaped object) is found by subtracting the area of the smaller, inner circle from the area of the larger, outer circle. </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_xjy7tsa8"> The formula is: </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_4tox43h8"> 
        <md>
            <mrow> A_\text{annulus} = \amp A_\text{outer circle} - A_\text{inner circle} </mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp \pi R^2 - \pi r^2 </mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp \pi (R^2 - r^2) </mrow> 
        </md> 
    </p> 
    <p xml:id="auto_af8fvgiy"> Where: <ul xml:id="auto_ogslfnio"> 
    <li xml:id="auto_6isof0n0"><m>R</m> is the radius of the outer circle</li> 
    <li xml:id="auto_xnhhqj5g"><m>r</m> is the radius of the inner circle</li> </ul> </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_0zrtkgb0">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ftbl5wrf">
            <alert>Objective:</alert> Learners apply the annulus formula to solve varied problems. Emphasise careful identification of <m>R</m> and <m>r</m>, and converting diameter to radius where needed.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_pkfqr6se">
            <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> Work through the first example on the board step by step. Allow learners to attempt the second example in pairs. Circulate and provide support as needed.
        </p>
    </axiom>
    
    <example xml:id="auto_5pw9zfux">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_6tjaha8v">
                Find the area of an the annulus drawn below;
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="Annulus3">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Outer circle in blue
                    \fill[cyan] (0,0) circle (3);
                    % Inner circle in white
                    \fill[white] (0,0) circle (1.8);
                    
                    % Radius lines
                    \draw[very thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (0:1.8) node[midway, above] {\textbf{$6$ cm}};
                    \draw[very thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (90:3) node[midway, right] {\textbf{$10$ cm}};
                    
                    % Center mark
                    \draw[thick] (-0.1,0) -- (0.1,0);
                    \draw[thick] (0,-0.1) -- (0,0.1);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_32xf80k9">
                <m>R=10\,cm</m> and <m>r=6\,cm</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_vqh92hhx">
                <md>
                    <mrow>A= \amp \pi(R^2-r^2) </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \pi(10^2-6^2) </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp  \pi(100-36)</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 64\pi </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp  64 \times \frac{22}{7}</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 201.06 \,cm^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
    <example xml:id="auto_z1bv4599">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_zv5hm3y5">
                A wheel has an outer radius of <m>40 \,cm</m>, and its inner hub  has a 
                radius of <m>10 \,cm</m>. Find the area of the wheel's annular region.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_wk37nv28">
                The outer radius of the wheel <m>= 40\,cm</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_zwsp2963">
                Inner hub radius <m>=10\,cm</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3ezrzahh">
                <md>
                    <mrow>A= \amp  \pi(R^2-r^2)</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{22}{7}(40^2-10^2) </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{22}{7}(1\,600-100)</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{22}{7} \times 1\,500 </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 4\,712.39 \,cm^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_ismhp9fu">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_nwgqq7ni">
            <alert>Instructions:</alert> Learners complete the exercises individually. Collect responses as an exit ticket.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8vtpfo2v">
            <alert>Answer Key (Teacher Reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gzrve2jd">
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_x68e365g"><p xml:id="auto_vhz4395d"><m>A = \pi(12^2 - 7^2) = 95\pi \approx 298.57\,m^2</m></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mps2t0ru"><p xml:id="auto_42za0n1j"><m>A = \pi(1.5^2 - 0.5^2) = 2\pi \approx 6.29\,m^2</m></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_at3nej7g"><p xml:id="auto_2fkth4zw"><m>A = \pi(8^2 - 2^2) = 60\pi \approx 188.57\,m^2</m></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_nx2uwybl"><p xml:id="auto_0zc8eqip">Convert diameters to radii: <m>R = 40</m>, <m>r = 30</m>. <m>A = \pi(40^2 - 30^2) = 700\pi \approx 2\,200</m> units<m>^2</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ihdanklx"><p xml:id="auto_isg3c5sp">Inner radius <m>= 20</m> in, width <m>= 15</m> in, so <m>R = 35</m> in. <m>A = 3.142(35^2 - 20^2) = 3.142 \times 825 \approx 2\,592.15</m> in<m>^2</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2gqxz29v"><p xml:id="auto_7eths7ly"><m>A = \pi(9^2 - 6^2) = 45\pi \approx 141\,cm^2</m> (3 s.f.).</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A ring-shaped garden has an outer radius of <m>12</m> meters and an inner radius of <m>7</m> meters. Find the area of the garden. 
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>298.49 \;\text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A circular tabletop has a hole in the middle for an umbrella. The outer radius of the table is <m>1.5 \,\text{m}</m>, and the hole has a radius of <m>0.5 \;\text{m}</m> as shown below.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="Annulus4">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Outer circle
                        \fill[cyan] (0,0) circle (3);
                        % Inner hole
                        \fill[white] (0,0) circle (1);
                        
                        % Radius lines
                        \draw[thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (0:1) node[midway, above] {\textbf{$0.5$ m}};
                        \draw[thick,-&gt;] (0,0) -- (150:3) node[midway, above] {\textbf{$1.5$ m}};
                        
                        % Center mark
                        \draw[thick] (-0.1,0) -- (0.1,0);
                        \draw[thick] (0,-0.1) -- (0,0.1);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                    
                </image>
                <p>
                    Find the area of the tabletop.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>6.284 \;\text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A circular swimming pool has an outer radius of <m>8</m> meters, 
                    and a smaller circular island is in the center with 
                    a radius of <m>2</m> meters. Find the area of the water surface.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>188.52 \;\text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A steel pipe has an outer diameter of <m>80</m> units and an inner diameter of
                    <m>60</m> units, what is the area of the cross-section?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>2199.4</m> square units
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the area of the figure below; use <m>\pi=3.142</m>
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="Annulus6">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Draw the outer circle in light blue
                        \fill[cyan!50] (0,0) circle (3.25);
                        % Draw the inner circle in white
                        \fill[white] (0,0) circle (2.5);
                        
                        % Draw radius lines and labels
                        \draw[thick, dashed] (-2.5,2) -- (-1.5,2) node[midway, above] {\textbf{15 in}};
                        \draw[thick, dashed] (-2.5,0) -- (0,0) node[midway, above] {\textbf{20 in}};
                        
                        % Center mark
                        \draw[thick] (-0.15,0) -- (0.15,0);
                        \draw[thick] (0,-0.15) -- (0,0.15);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                    
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>549.85 \;\text{in}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What is the area of the annulus shown; (Leave your answer to <m>3</m> 
                    significant figures).
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="Annulus7">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Draw the outer circle with light blue fill
                        \fill[yellow!30] (0,0) circle (4.5);
                        % Draw the inner circle with white fill
                        \fill[white] (0,0) circle (3);
                        
                        % Draw the outer and inner circle outlines
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (4.5);
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (3);
                        
                        % Draw the radius lines
                        \draw[dashed, thick] (0,0) -- (3,0) node[midway, above] {\textbf{6 cm}};
                        \draw[dashed, thick] (0,0) -- (-3.9,2.4) node[midway, right] {\textbf{9 cm}};
                        
                        % Draw center point
                        \filldraw (0,0) circle (2pt);
                        
                        % Mark the end points of radius lines
                        \filldraw (3,0) circle (2pt);
                        \filldraw (-3.9,2.4) circle (2pt);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>141 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    
